What is CloudFront in AWS?

Amazon CloudFront is a CDN (Content Delivery Network) service that delivers content to users faster by caching it at edge locations closer to them.

In EKS?

When you create CloudFront distribution you give the ALB DNS as the origin:

Route 53
  myapp.com → CloudFront domain
                    ↓
              CloudFront
                    ↓
              Origin: ALB DNS
                    ↓
                   ALB
                    ↓
                EKS Pods

Why use CloudFront in front of ALB:

| Feature               | Benefit                       |
| --------------------- | ----------------------------- |
| CDN caching           | Static files served from edge |
| Global edge locations | Low latency worldwide         |
| DDoS protection       | AWS Shield built in           |
| WAF integration       | Block malicious traffic       |
| SSL termination       | HTTPS at edge                 |
| Cost reduction        | Less traffic hits ALB         |

does it support NLB?

Claude responded: Yes!
Yes! CloudFront supports NLB as an origin — but with a condition:

Problem with NLB + CloudFront:

NLB is Layer 4 (TCP only)
    ↓
CloudFront is Layer 7 (HTTP/HTTPS)
    ↓
Mismatch!

CloudFront expects HTTP/HTTPS responses
NLB just passes TCP traffic
    ↓
NGINX pod must handle SSL ← extra config needed

That's why ALB is preferred over NLB for CloudFront:

CloudFront + ALB:
  Both Layer 7 ✅
  SSL at ALB ✅
  Clean integration ✅
  No extra config ✅

CloudFront + NLB:
  Layer mismatch ⚠️
  SSL must be at NGINX pod
  Extra config needed ⚠️
  Works but more complex

Nginx controller with ALB is best or NLB is best?

NGINX Controller with NLB is Better ✅

NGINX + NLB                    NGINX + ALB
───────────                    ───────────
✅ recommended                 ⚠️ not ideal
✅ your company uses this      ❌ avoid this combo
✅ makes sense                 ❌ redundant

